{"cursor":"36733","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\ns (grey) capped by telomeres (white)]]\n\nA 'telomere' is a region of repetitive nucleotide sequences at each end of a\nchromatid, which protects the end of the chromosome from deterioration or from\nfusion with neighboring chromosomes. Its name is derived from the Greek nouns\ntelos (ÏÎ­Î»Î¿Ï) 'end' and merÎ¿s (Î¼Î­ÏÎ¿Ï, root: Î¼ÎµÏ-) 'part.' Telomere regions deter\nthe degradation of genes near the ends of chromosomes by allowing chromosome\nends to shorten, which necessarily occurs during chromosome\nreplication. [http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=irUQEG4BSK4 AtGoogleTalks,\nAugust 20, 2008 Molecular biologist Elizabeth Blackburn] .. Without\ntelomeres, the genomes would progressively lose information and be truncated\nafter cell division because the synthesis of Ozaki strands requires RNA primers\nattaching ahead on the lagging strand. Over time, due to each cell division, the\ntelomere ends become shorter. Passarge, Eberhard. Color atlas of genetics,\n2007.\n\nDuring cell division, enzymes that duplicate DNA cannot continue their\nduplication all the way to the end of chromosomes. If cells divided without\ntelomeres, they would lose the ends of their chromosomes, and the necessary\ninformation they contain. The telomeres are disposable buffers blocking the ends\nof the chromosomes, are consumed during cell division, and are replenished by an\nenzyme, telomerase reverse transcriptase.\n","linknr":554,"url":"Telomere","recorded":1362480659,"links":64,"instances":["molecular_biology","aging"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Telomeres|","Repetitive DNA sequences","Chromosomes"],"headings":["Discovery","Nature and function","Shortening","Lengthening","Sequences","Cancer","Measurement","See also","References","Further reading","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4a/Telomere_caps.gif/300px-Telomere_caps.gif","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/im